Bumps [react-pdf](https://github.com/wojtekmaj/react-pdf/tree/HEAD/packages/react-pdf) from 9.2.1 to 10.1.0.
Release notes

Sourced from react-pdf's releases.

v10.1.0

What's new?

  • Added support for functions as children. React-PDF has never been simpler to work with! Say goodbye toonLoadSuccess, say goodbye to setting number of pages in your own state, say goodbye to extra renders! Now, rendering a simple document is as trivial as: 
    <Document file="sample.pdf">
  {({ pdf }) => Array(pdf.numPages)
    .fill(null)
    .map((_, index) => <Page key={index} pageIndex={index} />
  ))}
</Document>
    Thanks @â€‹adamaoc for inspiration!
  • Updated PDF.js to 5.3.93.
  • Updated documentation on JPEG 2000 support.
  • Updated dependencies.
  • Exported LinkService type for convenience.

What's changed?

  • usePageContext will now provide non-null value sooner than before, before the page is actually loaded. This is uniform with how useDocumentContext behaves and with how types were designed from the start, so you should not be affected by this change.
  • React-PDF now targets es2018 and not es2017. PDF.js, our core dependency, already used modern JavaScript syntax, so you should not be affected by this change.

v10.0.1

Bug fixes

  • Fixed commonly used types not reexported.

v10.0.0

See Upgrade guide from version 9.x to 10.x.

After more than a year since our last major release, we're thrilled to bring you React-PDF 10.

This update includes a major PDF.js upgrade, new features to make your life easier, improved stability, and some important breaking changes.

  • â—ï¸ Dropped CommonJS build, making the package ESM-only. Chances are you're not going to be affected by this change at all, as all common bundlers support ESM out of the box.
    • However, you may encounter issues running unit tests using Jest. Consider migrating to Vitest.
  • Updated PDF.js to 5.3.31.
    • Performance boosts: Key rendering routines refactored to cut memory usage and speed up page loading.
    • JPEG2000 downscaling: Automatic downscale of large JPEG2000 images during decoding to improve render times.
    • CMYK JPEG fix: Correct handling of the alpha channel when WebAssembly is disabled.
    • Viewer stability: Better handling of missing/invalid Content-Range headers.
    • API cleanup: Removed deprecated options, adopted parameter objects for core methods, and introduced private class fields for cleaner code.
  • Added support for scale prop in Document component, allowing you to set the scale for the entire document.

issue.title: Neovim format on save does not work
issue.body:
### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [x] I have searched the existing issues

### Platform

Apple Silicon macOS (darwin-arm64, Most Common)

### Editor

Neovim

### Editor Version

v0.11.3

### Describe the bug

As mentioned in [this](https://neovim.io/doc/user/lsp.html#lsp-attach) example, I have the following added to my neovim config to enable formatting the current buffer when it is saved:
```lua
vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('LspAttach', {
  group = vim.api.nvim_create_augroup('UserLspConfig', {}),
  callback = function(args)
    local client = vim.lsp.get_client_by_id(args.data.client_id)
    if client ~= nil and client:supports_method('textDocument/formatting') then
      vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('BufWritePre', {
        buffer = args.buf,
        callback = function()
          vim.lsp.buf.format({ bufnr = args.buf, id = client.id, async = false })
        end,
        desc = "Format the current buffer on save",
      })
    end
  end,
})
```
However, this feature does not work with tinymist. If I comment out `if client ~= nil and client:supports_method('textDocument/formatting') then` and its corresponding `end` then it works. My lsp logs contain `formatter_mode: Disable` and then a few lines down contain`"formatterMode":"typstyle"`. I suspect the issue lies in the fact that the client does not initially support `textDocument/formatting`, but after the tinymist config is parsed, this is enabled.

An example of an another lsp client which supports formatting as a config option but does not suffer from this issue is lua language server (lua_ls). Just mentioning this in case examining their setup helps in resolving this issue.

commits.message:
fix(payments): Implement self-healing for legacy data conflicts

This commit introduces a robust, self-healing mechanism within the
`update_pending_payment` service function. This resolves a cascade of
bugs, including database `IntegrityError` crashes and `Invalid parameter`
errors in Core Lightning logs, caused by legacy data inconsistencies.

The Bug:
A previous bug in the application logic led to the creation of
inconsistent records in the `apipayments` table. For a single
transaction, two records could exist:
1. A "buggy" record where `checking_id` was a UUID.
2. A "correct" record where `checking_id` was the proper payment hash.

This data corruption caused two major issues:
- When checking a buggy record's status, the UUID was sent to the
  Lightning node, causing it to fail. This left payments stuck in a
  "pending" state indefinitely in the UI.
- Attempts to repair these records via a simple `UPDATE` would cause a
  database `IntegrityError`, as it would violate the unique key
  constraint (`wallet_id`, `checking_id`) if a correct record already
  existed. This would crash the background task or API call.

The Fix:
Instead of requiring manual database cleanup, this fix implements a
"heal-on-read" strategy directly within `update_pending_payment`. When this
function encounters a potentially buggy record (where `checking_id` is
not equal to `payment_hash`):

1. It first queries the database to check for the existence of a
   "correct" duplicate record (where `checking_id` matches the hash).
2. If a correct duplicate is found, the current buggy record is identified
   as a redundant artifact and is safely deleted from the database.
3. If no correct duplicate is found, the buggy record is considered the
   sole entry for that payment and is repaired in-memory before its
   status is checked against the funding source.

This logic is wrapped in a `try/except` block to ensure that any single
payment processing error will not crash the entire background task, making
the system more resilient.

Why It Won't Break Anything:
This approach is significantly safer than previous attempts. It does not
aggressively modify data. Instead, it inspects the state of the database
and makes an intelligent decision: either delete a confirmed duplicate or
safely repair a lone inconsistent record.

This resolves both the `IntegrityError` (by deleting the source of the
conflict) and the Core Lightning errors (by ensuring `check_status` is
always called with a valid payment hash). The fix is contained and
targets the exact point of failure, automatically cleaning up legacy data
over time without requiring any user intervention.

issue.title: Bug: check_table forcing input to convert to data.table
issue.body:
When running a function that uses `check_table`, if the input argument is not a data.table then it gets converted to a data.table. This is fine for within the function, however `setDT` has a side-effect where the object outside of the function call also gets converted to a data.table (this function updates the object by reference rather than by assignment). This is causing issues in a project where other functions/modules are expecting a data.frame rather than a data.table.

If `check_table` is returning the table in every call, then can replace with `as.data.table`, otherwise it is best to copy the input object before running `setDT` to maintain the structure of the original object.

Example:

```r
library(dtlg)
```

comment.body:
Hi Ashley, hi Max,

Thanks for raising this â€” I think I need a bit of clarification to fully understand the motivation behind the proposed change.

From my side, my understanding was that one of the main design choices in dtlg was to embrace `data.table` efficiency, including in-place modification with `setDT()`. This avoids unnecessary copies and is generally faster. If we switch to `as.data.table()`, we lose that efficiency because it makes a copy. That seems to go against one of the core tenets of the package.

The current behaviour does indeed mean that if you pass in a `data.frame` or `tibble`, it will be converted by reference to a `data.table`. Since `data.table` inherits from `data.frame`, I didnâ€™t initially see this as problematic, especially given that the functions here are meant to produce â€œend-of-the-lineâ€ summary tables for display, not necessarily objects to be reused downstream.

That said, I see the dilemma:

- With `setDT()`: we get efficiency, but at the cost of side effects (the input object is permanently changed).

- With `as.data.table()`: we avoid side effects and remain closer to a â€œpure functionâ€ style, but we pay the price in performance and memory copies.

So it comes down to which principle we want to prioritise for this package: maximum efficiency, or strict avoidance of side effects. Both are valid, but they pull in different directions.

Would it make sense to (a) document the current side-effect clearly, so users know their inputs will be converted to data.table, or (b) add an option or helper for users who really want to preserve the original input type?

Curious to hear your thoughts â€” happy to adjust, but just wanted to flag the trade-off as I see it.

#### `as.data.table` makes a copy

``` r
iris2 <- iris

lobstr::obj_addrs(iris)
#> [1] "0x5e9ce3f17b90" "0x5e9ce43b5910" "0x5e9ce5bb9dd0" "0x5e9ce39ce1f0"
#> [5] "0x5e9ce6bc41b0"
lobstr::obj_addrs(iris2)
#> [1] "0x5e9ce3f17b90" "0x5e9ce43b5910" "0x5e9ce5bb9dd0" "0x5e9ce39ce1f0"
#> [5] "0x5e9ce6bc41b0"

lobstr::obj_addrs(data.table::setDT(iris2))
#> [1] "0x5e9ce3f17b90" "0x5e9ce43b5910" "0x5e9ce5bb9dd0" "0x5e9ce39ce1f0"
#> [5] "0x5e9ce6bc41b0"

lobstr::obj_addrs(data.table::as.data.table(iris2))
#> [1] "0x5e9ce5a2edc0" "0x5e9ce35fc920" "0x5e9ce427b3d0" "0x5e9ce3cc9650"
#> [5] "0x5e9ce3690ba0"
```

Also, note that the current state of the package uses `check_table()` early on in many functions but its role is not _checking_ that the input is a `data.table` but rather _ensuring_ that it is a `data.table`, and doing so by reference --- PR https://github.com/AscentSoftware/dtlg/pull/23 does change this aspect except for removing the unnecessary S3 dispatch.

pull_request.title: Corrected passing of mmax parameter in multipole_electrostatics
pull_request.body:
I am currently working on using **ddX** together with a **multipole-expanded solute density**. While implementing this, I noticed that in `multipole_electrostatics` the argument `mmax` is strictly passed as `mmax=0` to its subsequent subroutines. This prevents setting up a suitable potential beyond monopoles.

I corrected the corresponding arguments to use the more general `mmax`, which should already be defined when the host code calls the function. I suppose this was the original intention, since other routines in the `ddx_multipolar_solutes` module pass `mmax` as well. The routines `multipole_electrostatics_1`â€“`multipole_electrostatics_3` likewise expect `mmax` as an argument and do not need to be restricted to 0.

This should therefore be a straightforward bug fix and is not expected to introduce further issues.
